SIMPLE: sink
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sink
<hw>Sink</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Sunk</conjf> <pr>(s⟦ucr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, or
(<conjf>Sank</conjf> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>); <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sunk</conjf> (<mark>obs.</mark> <conjf>Sunken</conjf>, -- now
used as <pos>adj.</pos>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sinking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sinken</ets>, AS.
<ets>sincan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zinken</ets>, OS. <ets>sincan</ets>,
G. <ets>sinken</ets>, Icel. <ets>s⟦oum⟧kkva</ets>, Dan.
<ets>synke</ets>, Sw. <ets>sjunka</ets>, Goth. <ets>siggan</ets>, and
probably to E. <ets>silt</ets>. Cf. <er>Silt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To fall by, or as by, the force of gravity; to descend lower and
lower; to decline gradually; to subside; <as>as, a stone <ex>sinks</ex>
in water; waves rise and <ex>sink</ex>; the sun <ex>sinks</ex> in the
west</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>sink</qex> in deep mire.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxix.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter deeply; to fall or retire beneath or below
the surface; to penetrate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stone <qex>sunk</qex> into his forehead.</q> <rj><qau>1 San.
xvii. 49.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to enter so as to make an abiding impression;
to enter completely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let these sayings <qex>sink</qex> down into your ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke ix. 44.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be overwhelmed or depressed; to fall slowly, as
so the ground, from weakness or from an overburden; to fail in strength;
to decline; to decay; to decrease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I think our country <qex>sinks</qex> beneath the yoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>sunk</qex> down in his chariot.</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings ix.
24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not the fire <qex>sink</qex> or slacken.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To decrease in volume, as a river; to subside; to
become diminished in volume or in apparent height.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Alps and Pyreneans <qex>sink</qex> before him.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To fall; subside; drop; droop; lower; decline;
decay; decrease; lessen.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sink
<hw>Sink</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cause to sink; to put under water; to immerse or submerge in a
fluid; <as>as, to <ex>sink</ex> a ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The Athenians] fell upon the wings and <qex>sank</qex> a single
ship.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Figuratively: To cause to decline; to depress; to
degrade; hence, to ruin irretrievably; to destroy, as by drowning;
<as>as, to <ex>sink</ex> one's reputation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I raise of <qex>sink</qex>, imprison or set free.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I have a conscience, let it <qex>sink</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy cruel and unnatural lust of power⟦br⟧
Has <qex>sunk</qex> thy father more than all his years.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make (a depression) by digging, delving, or
cutting, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>sink</ex> a pit or a well; to
<ex>sink</ex> a die.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bring low; to reduce in quantity; to
waste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>sunk</qex> the river repeated draughts.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To conceal and appropriate.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If sent with ready money to buy anything, and you happen to be out
of pocket, <qex>sink</qex> the money, and take up the goods on
account.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To keep out of sight; to suppress; to
ignore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A courtly willingness to <qex>sink</qex> obnoxious truths.</q>
<rj><qau>Robertson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To reduce or extinguish by payment; <as>as, to
<ex>sink</ex> the national debt</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sink
<hw>Sink</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
drain to carry off filthy water; a jakes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A shallow box or vessel of wood, stone, iron, or
other material, connected with a drain, and used for receiving filthy
water, etc., as in a kitchen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hole or low place in land or rock, where waters
sink and are lost; -- called also <altname>sink hole</altname>.</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The lowest part of a natural hollow or closed basin
whence the water of one or more streams escapes by evaporation; <as>as,
the <ex>sink</ex> of the Humboldt River</as>.</def> <mark>[Western U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sink hole</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The opening to a
sink drain</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A cesspool</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>Same
as <er>Sink</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sinker</ent>⟦br⟧
